NOTES_JOEL = {
    1: {
        1: 'HEBREW: "The word of YHWH" (dabar YHWH, H1697 + H3068) is the standard prophetic reception formula, marking divine origin and authority. "Came" (hayah, H1961) indicates an active arriving or becoming, not merely passive reception. Joel ben Pethuel is otherwise unknown in Scripture, focusing attention on the message rather than the messenger\'s lineage.',
        4: 'HEBREW: Four distinct Hebrew terms for locusts are used: gazam (H1494, "cutter"), arbeh (H697, "swarmer," from rabah, "to multiply"), yeleq (H3218, "licker" or "hopper"), and hasil (H2625, "consumer" or "destroyer"). Whether these denote four species, four life stages of the locust, or a rhetorical fourfold intensification is debated; the cumulative effect emphasizes total devastation. TYPOLOGY: The fourfold locust plague echoes the Exodus plagues (Ex 10:1-20) and anticipates the four horsemen of Revelation 6, suggesting a pattern of escalating divine judgment in redemptive history.',
        6: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: The description of the locust army as a "nation" (goy, H1471) without number invites comparison with Joel 2\'s explicit depiction of YHWH\'s army. The lion imagery (H738, \'aryeh; H3833, labi\') evokes a supernatural destructive power behind the natural catastrophe, consistent with ANE divine warrior traditions where celestial armies manifest in earthly phenomena.',
        8: 'HEBREW: "Betulah" (H1330) denotes a young woman of marriageable age, most often a virgin. The image of mourning for the "husband of her youth" (ba\'al ne\'urim) presupposes a betrothed or newly-wed woman — the most acute form of grief in ancient Israelite culture. TYPOLOGY: The mourning bride anticipates the covenant lament motif: Israel as the unfaithful or afflicted bride of YHWH, which is developed in Hosea, Jeremiah, and ultimately resolved in Revelation 21:2.',
        9: 'THEOLOGICAL: The cessation of the minchah (grain offering, H4503) and nesek (drink offering, H5262) represents a covenantal catastrophe — the daily tamid offering that maintained Israel\'s ritual standing before YHWH is interrupted. This is not merely economic loss but a rupture in the liturgical life sustaining the covenant relationship. The priests\' mourning signals that heaven itself registers the breach.',
        14: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Atsarah" (H6116), variously translated "solemn assembly" or "sacred convocation," denotes a cultic gathering often associated with the cessation of ordinary labor and collective lamentation or petition. Joel\'s call to fast and assemble anticipates the fuller call of Joel 2:12-17, where YHWH invites genuine heart-return. TYPOLOGY: This assembly pattern — crisis, gathering, corporate lament, divine response — is paradigmatic for Israel\'s liturgical theology and is echoed in Nehemiah 9, Jonah 3, and ultimately in the church\'s practice of communal repentance.',
        15: 'THEOLOGICAL: "Yom YHWH" (the Day of YHWH) appears here for the first time in Joel and is the book\'s central theological concept. It is a day of YHWH\'s active intervention in history — simultaneously judgment and salvation depending on one\'s covenantal standing. "Shaddai" (H7706, the Almighty) is an archaic divine epithet evoking overwhelming, irresistible power, used deliberately here to stress the inescapable nature of the coming judgment. TYPOLOGY: This verse is foundational to all subsequent Day of YHWH theology in the prophets (Amos 5:18-20, Zeph 1:14-18, Mal 4:5) and finds its NT fulfillment trajectory in the Day of the Lord passages of 1 Thess 5:2, 2 Pet 3:10, and Rev 6:12-17.',
        19: 'THEOLOGICAL: The prophet\'s sudden first-person address to YHWH ("to you, O YHWH, I cry") marks a liturgical pivot from proclamation to petition, modeling the response the entire community is called to make in 2:12-17. The intercessory voice of the prophet on behalf of creation — beast, land, and people — anticipates the priestly-prophetic role of Christ who stands as advocate before the Father (1 John 2:1). HEBREW: "Devoured" (akalah, H398) and "burned" (lahatah, H3857) suggest both literal fire (possibly drought-induced) and the consuming presence of divine judgment, a dual register common in prophetic poetry.',
        20: 'HEBREW: "Ta\'arog" (H6165) means "to long for" or "to pant after" with intense yearning, the same root used in Psalm 42:1 ("As the deer pants for flowing streams, so pants my soul for you, O God"). The use of this term for the beasts\' longing toward YHWH creates a profound theological irony: even creation instinctively cries out to its Creator while the human community must be summoned to do so. THEOLOGICAL: This verse closes the chapter with a note of creation\'s solidarity in suffering (Rom 8:19-22), pointing forward to the eschatological restoration where the whole created order is renewed under YHWH\'s reign.',
    },
    2: {
        1: 'HEBREW: "Shofar" (Strong\'s H7782) is the ram\'s horn trumpet, the covenantal alarm instrument. "My holy mountain" identifies Zion as YHWH\'s cosmic dwelling, echoing the divine council\'s mountain of assembly (Isa 14:13). The "day of YHWH" (yom YHWH) is the foundational eschatological concept of Joel, denoting YHWH\'s direct intervention in history as divine warrior and judge. THEOLOGICAL: The trumpet blast as alarm signals the reversal of the priestly blessing function (Num 10:9); Zion, typically the place of salvation proclamation, here becomes the platform for a terror announcement, underscoring the gravity of the approaching judgment.',
        2: 'HISTORICAL: The imagery of an invading locust army (or metaphorical military force) advancing like "dawn spread upon the mountains" reflects ANE battle descriptions. The incomparability formula ("there has not been the like") echoes the Exodus plagues (Exod 10:14), deliberately casting this judgment as a new, surpassing Exodus-of-wrath. THEOLOGICAL: The phrase "generation upon generation" (dor va-dor) emphasizes the unprecedented and final character of this judgment, framing it within the eschatological telos of history.',
        3: 'TYPOLOGY: The before/after contrast — Eden to wilderness — inverts the creation and redemption narrative. Eden represents the state of divine blessing (Gen 2), while the ensuing desolation pictures de-creation. This anticipates the ultimate reversal: the new creation in Christ restoring Eden (Rev 22:1-5). The motif of no survivor foreshadows the absolute nature of the final Day of YHWH judgment.',
        11: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: YHWH\'s "army" (chayil) here is his heavenly host executing his sovereign decree. The motif of YHWH commanding a celestial/cosmic army before whom the earth trembles is rooted in divine council theology (Ps 103:20-21; Isa 13:3-5). "Who can endure it?" is a rhetorical question implying that no unaided human being can stand before the divine warrior — only those granted covenant standing survive. THEOLOGICAL: YHWH\'s voice (qol) preceding the army recalls the theophanic thunderstorm imagery of Ps 29, where YHWH\'s voice shakes creation.',
        13: 'HEBREW: "Rachum" (Strong\'s H7349) — merciful, from the root rechem (womb), connoting deep, maternal compassion. "Hesed" (Strong\'s H2617) — steadfast covenant love, loyalty, lovingkindness; untranslatable by a single English word. This verse quotes the divine self-disclosure of Exod 34:6-7, the foundational covenant character formula repeated throughout the OT (Ps 86:15; Jon 4:2; Neh 9:17). THEOLOGICAL: The call to rend hearts rather than garments is a radical internalization of covenant repentance, anticipating the new covenant of the heart (Jer 31:33; Ezek 36:26).',
        17: 'HISTORICAL: The location "between the vestibule and the altar" is the precise inner court space of the Jerusalem Temple, making this a formal liturgical lament. This is the space where priests ministered daily, now transformed into a place of communal grief. THEOLOGICAL: The petition "Why should they say among the peoples, \'Where is their God?\'" is a covenant honor argument — the nations\' mockery impugns YHWH\'s name and reputation (cf. Ps 79:10; Ezek 36:20-23), which becomes the grounds for YHWH\'s response of salvation.',
        23: 'HEBREW: "Moreh" (Strong\'s H4175) is disputed — it can mean "early rain" or "teacher for righteousness." The rabbis and some scholars read this as a messianic teacher of righteousness, while the agricultural reading (early rain) fits the immediate context. The dual meaning is likely intentional, foreshadowing both physical restoration and spiritual instruction. The "latter rain" (malkosh) refers to the spring rains critical for the final ripening of the harvest. TYPOLOGY: The outpouring of rain anticipates the Spirit\'s outpouring in v. 28; water and Spirit are linked in new covenant theology (Isa 44:3; John 7:37-39).',
        25: 'HEBREW: Four distinct Hebrew terms for the locust are used across Joel 1-2: gazam (cutter/gnawer), arbeh (swarming locust, the most common term), yelek (hopper/licker), and chasil (destroyer/consumer). Scholars debate whether these are different species or different life stages of the locust. THEOLOGICAL: YHWH\'s identification of the locusts as "my great army which I sent" reframes natural disaster as divine instrument, a key theological move asserting YHWH\'s absolute sovereignty over creation and history.',
        28: 'HEBREW: "Ruach" (Strong\'s H7307) — Spirit, wind, breath; the animating divine presence and power. "All flesh" (kol-basar) is an extraordinary universalizing statement within an OT context where the Spirit was given selectively to prophets, priests, and kings. TYPOLOGY: This is the key messianic-eschatological promise quoted by Peter at Pentecost (Acts 2:17-21) as the definitive fulfillment event inaugurated by the exaltation of Jesus the Messiah (Acts 2:33). The pouring out of the Spirit upon all flesh — without regard to gender, age, or social status — constitutes the new covenant community\'s charter.',
        29: 'THEOLOGICAL: The extension of the Spirit\'s outpouring to male and female servants (avadim and shiphachot) is a radical social leveling that would have been striking in the ANE hierarchy. This democratization of prophetic access anticipates Gal 3:28 and signals the eschatological age\'s dissolution of barriers that restricted covenant participation. The Spirit\'s gift is now the universal mark of covenant membership.',
        30: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: "Wonders in the heavens and in the earth" (mophethim) signals upheaval in both the earthly and heavenly realms — the cosmic theater in which YHWH executes judgment. Blood, fire, and smoke are theophanic battle imagery associated with YHWH\'s divine warrior role (Exod 19:18; Ps 18:8-15). THEOLOGICAL: These cosmic signs are referenced in Rev 6:12-17 and 8:7 as seals of the final judgment, establishing Joel as a structural source for Johannine apocalypticism.',
        31: 'THEOLOGICAL: "The sun shall be turned to darkness and the moon to blood" constitutes cosmic-sign language signaling the imminent arrival of the eschatological Day of YHWH. This language is taken up directly in Jesus\'s Olivet Discourse (Matt 24:29; Mark 13:24-25) and Rev 6:12, indicating that cosmic disruption accompanies and heralds the climactic divine intervention in history. The phrase "before the great and awesome day of YHWH" situates these signs as precursors, not the event itself.',
        32: 'HEBREW: "Everyone who calls upon the name of YHWH shall be saved (yimmalet)" — the verb malat means to escape, to be delivered, to be saved. "The name of YHWH" (shem YHWH) is not a mere title but the full person, character, and covenant presence of YHWH. TYPOLOGY: Paul quotes this verse in Rom 10:13, applying "YHWH" to the Lord Jesus Christ — one of the most direct NT identifications of Jesus with YHWH of the OT. Peter likewise cites it at Pentecost (Acts 2:21). The survivors on Zion whom "YHWH calls" (yiqra) introduces the concept of divine election as the basis of covenant salvation.',
    },
    3: {
        1: 'HEBREW: "Restore the fortunes" renders shebut (שְׁבוּת, Strong\'s H7622), a term meaning "captivity" or "turning of fortune," suggesting both a return from exile and a comprehensive covenantal restoration. THEOLOGICAL: This verse opens the eschatological section of Joel and frames the cosmic judgment of chapter 3 as inseparable from YHWH\'s redemptive purpose for his people, establishing the Day of YHWH as simultaneously a day of salvation for Israel and of judgment for the nations.',
        2: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: "Valley of Jehoshaphat" (יְהוֹשָׁפָט, "YHWH judges") is not a firmly identified geographical location but a theological toponym — the place where YHWH renders his sovereign verdict over the nations. THEOLOGICAL: The assembly of all nations before YHWH for judicial sentencing reflects the divine council imagery in which YHWH presides as supreme Judge (Ps 82:1, Dan 7:9-10). The indictment centers on the scattering of Israel and the partition of YHWH\'s land (eretz), asserting his proprietary claim over both people and territory.',
        3: 'HISTORICAL: The selling of children for a prostitute\'s fee or a skin of wine reflects ancient Near Eastern practices of debt-slavery and war-captivity trafficking. THEOLOGICAL: The casual commodification of human persons made in the image of God (imago Dei) intensifies the moral indictment; YHWH takes personal offense at the mistreatment of his covenant people as though they were worthless chattel.',
        9: 'THEOLOGICAL: The ironic inversion of the messianic peace oracle (Mic 4:3, Isa 2:4) — "beat plowshares into swords" — signals that this is a summons to the nations\' self-destruction rather than a genuine call to arms. TYPOLOGY: The "consecrated war" (milhamah qadash) anticipates the final eschatological conflict, foreshadowed in Revelation 16:14-16 (the gathering at Armageddon).',
        10: 'TYPOLOGY: This verse deliberately inverts Isaiah 2:4 and Micah 4:3, where swords are beaten into plowshares under the Messiah\'s reign. The reversal here is not YHWH\'s ideal but a judicial summons — the nations are called to muster their full military strength only to be shattered. THEOLOGICAL: The command "let the weak say I am a mighty man" may be darkly ironic: no human strength avails before YHWH\'s judgment.',
        11: 'DIVINE_COUNCIL: "Bring down, O YHWH, your mighty ones (gibborim)" is best read as a prayer interrupting the battle summons, calling on YHWH to deploy his heavenly warrior host — the divine council\'s military retinue (cf. Ps 103:20-21, Zech 14:5, Rev 19:14). HEBREW: gibborim (גִּבֹּרִים, Strong\'s H1368) means "mighty men, heroes, warriors," used both of elite human soldiers and of angelic/divine beings in contexts of cosmic warfare.',
        13: 'TYPOLOGY: The harvest and winepress imagery is directly taken up in Revelation 14:14-20, where the Son of Man swings his sickle over the earth and angels tread the great winepress of the wrath of God. THEOLOGICAL: The double image of grain harvest and grape vintage signals comprehensive, total judgment — nothing escapes. The overflowing vats represent the superabundance of human wickedness demanding a proportional divine response.',
        14: 'HEBREW: "Valley of decision" (עֵמֶק הֶחָרוּץ, emeq he-haruts) comes from haruts (Strong\'s H2742), meaning "incised, sharp, decided" — often rendered "threshing," suggesting a verdict already cut and fixed. THEOLOGICAL: The doubled "multitudes, multitudes" (hamonim hamonim) is an emphatic intensification conveying the vast, unprecedented scale of the eschatological gathering. The Day of YHWH is not contingent but decreed.',
        15: 'THEOLOGICAL: The darkening of sun, moon, and stars is a recurring cosmic-sign motif in Day of YHWH texts (Joel 2:10, 31; Isa 13:10; Matt 24:29; Rev 6:12-13), signaling the unraveling of the created order before YHWH\'s theophanic presence. DIVINE_COUNCIL: In the ancient Near Eastern worldview, celestial bodies were associated with divine beings; their extinguishing suggests the demotion and disempowerment of rival cosmic powers before YHWH (cf. Isa 24:21-23).',
        16: 'HEBREW: mahoz (מָעוֹז, Strong\'s H4581) means "stronghold, refuge, place of strength," from oz (strength). The same root appears in Psalm 27:1 and Nahum 1:7. THEOLOGICAL: The cosmic theophany — YHWH roaring from Zion — results not in the terror of his people but in their protection; divine wrath and divine shelter coexist in the same event, distinguishing the recipients of grace from the objects of judgment.',
        17: 'THEOLOGICAL: YHWH\'s self-identification ("I am YHWH your God") echoes the Sinai covenant formula, tying eschatological fulfillment to covenantal origin. The holiness of Jerusalem and the exclusion of strangers from her describes a consummated state — a restored exclusivity of divine presence, fulfilled ultimately in the New Jerusalem (Rev 21:27). TYPOLOGY: "Strangers shall pass through her no more" anticipates the permanent, undefiled community of the redeemed.',
        18: 'TYPOLOGY: The fountain flowing from the house of YHWH watering the Valley of Shittim anticipates Ezekiel 47:1-12 and Revelation 22:1-2, where the river of life flows from the throne of God through the restored creation. THEOLOGICAL: The extravagant fertility imagery — mountains dripping wine, hills flowing with milk — reverses the locust-and-drought curse of Joel 1-2, signaling that the eschatological blessing is not merely agricultural but covenantal shalom (שָׁלוֹם) poured out upon redeemed land and people.',
        21: 'THEOLOGICAL: The final verse anchors every promise and judgment in the one non-negotiable fact: "YHWH dwells in Zion." Divine presence is the ultimate eschatological reality from which all restoration flows. TYPOLOGY: The avenging of innocent blood points forward to Christ\'s atoning work, through which the blood of the innocent (his own) paradoxically becomes the ground of acquittal for his people rather than condemnation (Heb 12:24), and the ground of judgment upon all who despise it.',
    },
}